  {
    "speaker": "interviewee",
    "tag": "EC",
    "text": "'It was difficult growing up as a child of survivors because all the other children had grandparents to visit and share holidays with. I hadn't known my grandparents, and I missed having a great deal of family. I'm very proud that after all the sturm und drang and all the struggling that my parents had made a life for themselves in a new country, that they came to a country where they did not know people and did not know the language and succeeded so well in making a good life. We're now teaching our children about the Holocaust so that they can know and be proud of their grandparents as well. I think that my mother does a wonderful job keeping the Holocaust memory alive and all the causes that she works on. I'm very proud of my parents. And again, I think the most difficult part was not knowing more of my family and not having more family to share.' [PAUSES FOR 6 SECONDS] This is my granddaughter Lauren, who was born in February of 1987 in New Jersey.",
